1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,140
 So now we're going to do a bit of a deep dive into the machine language of our CDC 6504 emulator.

2
00:00:06,140 --> 00:00:15,180
 I would suggest that if you're doing extensive work or even if you have some visual limitations that you look at the online documentation.

3
00:00:15,180 --> 00:00:25,000
 It's complete and it's simple and to some degree this lecture is really derived from the online documentation of the CDC 6504.

4
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:28,840
 And so we always are going to start and talk about the register and just review it.

5
00:00:28,840 --> 00:00:32,200
 Hopefully after a couple of lectures, it'll be sort of natural to you.

6
00:00:32,200 --> 00:00:37,500
 The program counter is the what next, instruction memory starts at zero.

7
00:00:37,500 --> 00:00:40,540
 The accumulator is the best register.

8
00:00:40,540 --> 00:00:51,240
 So it's the CDC 6504 is an accumulator based computer, which means that you can do more things with the accumulator than other registers.

9
00:00:51,240 --> 00:00:57,800
 There are flags, the Z and the N and there's actually more in the 6502, but Z and the N is all I put in here.

10
00:00:57,800 --> 00:01:04,300
 Z says when you're fiddling with registers, was the last result zero or was the last result negative?

11
00:01:04,300 --> 00:01:09,340
 And these are used to control ifs and jumps and loops, the Z and the N.

12
00:01:09,340 --> 00:01:11,540
 The X and the Y are index registers.

13
00:01:11,540 --> 00:01:18,100
 They're just a little less capable of the accumulator register and they're actually used in index loads, as we'll see.

14
00:01:18,100 --> 00:01:21,760
 Instruction memory is shown in base two for easy decoding.

15
00:01:21,760 --> 00:01:29,840
 Now the data memory, I show that in hex because mostly what we're putting in the data memory is strings and ASCII characters.

16
00:01:29,840 --> 00:01:41,400
 OK, so the index instructions are good for loops and the X and Y registers are often used to control counted loops or actually look things up within an array.

17
00:01:41,400 --> 00:01:51,500
 And so we have an opcode to clear the X register, clear the Y register, add one to it, add one to X and Y and then subtract one from X and Y.

18
00:01:51,500 --> 00:01:59,600
 Now, if you think about it, the CPU that we built clears and increments with two instructions.

19
00:01:59,600 --> 00:02:04,960
 So we had an instruction of one which increments and zero which clears.

20
00:02:04,960 --> 00:02:09,840
 So in addition to 8-bit instructions, there are 16-bit instructions.

21
00:02:09,840 --> 00:02:17,460
 And so in 16-bit instructions, there is usually a numeric value or a constant or an address that is in the immediately following.

22
00:02:17,460 --> 00:02:21,960
 So that means that the program counter in this case goes up by two.

23
00:02:21,960 --> 00:02:26,960
 And so the load A instruction can take a constant value.

24
00:02:26,960 --> 00:02:31,460
 So you can load A, the character asterisk, which is 42.

25
00:02:31,460 --> 00:02:35,260
 And so you see the load A instruction at memory location zero.

26
00:02:35,260 --> 00:02:40,800
 And then the actual 42 value, in this case base two, is instruction one.

27
00:02:40,800 --> 00:02:50,160
 Or you can basically say we're going to do a load, but the address that we want to load from is taken from the following 8-bits.

28
00:02:50,160 --> 00:02:56,860
 In this case, we're going to load from memory location two and the two is stored in instruction memory location three.

29
00:02:56,860 --> 00:02:58,760
 So we call these immediate.

30
00:02:58,760 --> 00:03:05,700
 And the reason we kind of call these things immediate is the constant or the address is immediately following the instruction in case.

31
00:03:05,700 --> 00:03:08,500
 And so these turn into 16-bit instructions.

32
00:03:08,500 --> 00:03:15,460
 You can see it as you load one instruction in and there will probably be both a current instruction register and an immediate register.

33
00:03:15,460 --> 00:03:21,360
 And you would notice that this instruction that we just loaded has an immediate.

34
00:03:21,360 --> 00:03:27,260
 And so we'd load both of those things and then have them in the CPU to work.

35
00:03:27,260 --> 00:03:31,360
 So loading and storing operations are important.

36
00:03:31,360 --> 00:03:40,040
 So you can load into the A register, the X register, and the Y register, and you can store into the A register, X register, and Y register.

37
00:03:40,040 --> 00:03:46,440
 And you can either load a constant like set A to zero, load A, hashtag zero.

38
00:03:46,440 --> 00:03:53,700
 Or you can say go get memory location F3 and load that in.

39
00:03:53,700 --> 00:03:56,900
 And so those are the instructions that do loading and storing.

40
00:03:56,900 --> 00:04:01,900
 Now, when we start dealing with the arrays, we can use the X and the Y.

41
00:04:01,900 --> 00:04:07,740
 So we can say this address is kind of the beginning of the array and then X and Y are the offset in the array.

42
00:04:07,740 --> 00:04:11,260
 So you start seeing that you can set X to zero.

43
00:04:11,260 --> 00:04:21,160
 You can load something from a starting point in memory plus X and then you can add one to zero and then load something again from that same place in memory plus X.

44
00:04:21,160 --> 00:04:29,540
 And then X become and Y are really well designed to use as iteration variables.

45
00:04:29,540 --> 00:04:35,700
 And then this is where the accumulator is important, where the accumulator is the register that can do the most things.

46
00:04:35,700 --> 00:04:44,300
 So we can't add arbitrary values, so we can't add we can add one to X and Y registers, but we can't add five.

47
00:04:44,300 --> 00:04:48,180
 So ADC hashtag five adds five to it.

48
00:04:48,180 --> 00:04:57,800
 So the same for subtraction and that you can either add an immediate value like a constant or you can go into some memory and grab that memory and add it to the accumulator.

49
00:04:57,800 --> 00:05:03,420
 So you can see it says ACC equals ACC plus memory bracket address.

50
00:05:03,420 --> 00:05:07,220
 That means that we're adding in the data memory at the position that's address.

51
00:05:07,220 --> 00:05:09,780
 But the address, it's an immediate instruction.

52
00:05:09,780 --> 00:05:12,140
 And the next one is the address that we're going to add.

53
00:05:12,140 --> 00:05:16,060
 So adding and subtracting is the accumulator.

54
00:05:16,060 --> 00:05:26,820
 Now, the everything that is adding, subtracting, loading, storing, whatever is doing to whatever register sets the Z and the N flags.

55
00:05:26,820 --> 00:05:33,780
 And so it just as part of the final putting the value into the register, it sets Z and N.

56
00:05:33,780 --> 00:05:38,980
 So if the value we put in to the register was zero, the Z flag will be a one.

57
00:05:38,980 --> 00:05:44,020
 It'll be set. If the value we put in was 42, the Z flag will be zero.

58
00:05:44,020 --> 00:05:50,560
 And the same with positive and negative. Negative numbers are numbers that have the first bit, the tie bit one.

59
00:05:50,560 --> 00:05:53,900
 We're not doing too much. We won't be doing too much with negative in this class.

60
00:05:53,900 --> 00:06:00,380
 We'll mostly be setting the zero. But you can do like less than or equal with the negative.

61
00:06:00,380 --> 00:06:06,940
 So combinations of Z and N can do greater than or equal, less than or equal, et cetera, et cetera.

62
00:06:06,940 --> 00:06:16,980
 And so there is a special instruction called the compare instruction that says, hey, let's check to see if the accumulator equals five.

63
00:06:16,980 --> 00:06:20,740
 But you're really saying five accumulator, check them.

64
00:06:20,740 --> 00:06:25,860
 It's kind of like a subtraction without actually doing the subtraction and then set subtract,

65
00:06:25,860 --> 00:06:31,460
 set the Z and N flags from the result of the subtraction and then throw away the result of the subtraction.

66
00:06:31,460 --> 00:06:41,180
 So that's what the comparison operators are. OK. And so you can compare the accumulator, the X and the Y.

67
00:06:41,180 --> 00:06:46,780
 So there's no if statement in machine code. All there are are conditional jumps.

68
00:06:46,780 --> 00:06:53,660
 And so that you have to get used to it. When I started in Fortran, everything was a go to before we had structured ifs, if then else.

69
00:06:53,660 --> 00:06:59,260
 That that's not in machine code. There is a conditional jump, which we'll talk about.

70
00:06:59,260 --> 00:07:08,900
 And the way you get the conditional jumps to activate is every instruction that changes a register and the compare instructions with don't change registers, set the result flags.

71
00:07:08,900 --> 00:07:16,220
 There's a Z, which is was the result zero or not. And then the N is was the result negative or not.

72
00:07:16,220 --> 00:07:20,420
 And so if the result is zero, the Z is one and the N is zero because zero is not negative.

73
00:07:20,420 --> 00:07:25,540
 If the result is positive, Z is zero because it's not zero and N is zero because it's not negative.

74
00:07:25,540 --> 00:07:30,740
 And if the result is negative, Z is zero and one is negative.

75
00:07:30,740 --> 00:07:37,540
 And yes, you can use these together to create greater than, greater than or equal to, equal, less than, less than or equal to.

76
00:07:37,540 --> 00:07:47,980
 So that's kind of what you're thinking about, right, is how to implement what we think of as the traditional logical operators in a high level language.

77
00:07:47,980 --> 00:07:55,420
 So the closest we have to an if statement is a compare and then a conditional jump.

78
00:07:55,420 --> 00:08:00,500
 And so there are four instructions, right?

79
00:08:00,500 --> 00:08:02,940
 There's more of them, but these are the four that matter.

80
00:08:02,940 --> 00:08:07,260
 The B, E, Q, branch if equal, that means the Z flag is set.

81
00:08:07,260 --> 00:08:11,900
 B, N, E, branch if not equal means the Z flag is clear.

82
00:08:11,900 --> 00:08:17,340
 And then branch minus B, M, I, and then B, P, L means branch plus.

83
00:08:17,340 --> 00:08:22,620
 So, for example, here's a little tiny bit of code that we can do an uppercase.

84
00:08:22,620 --> 00:08:26,780
 We're going to convert a lowercase to uppercase and leave uppercase alone.

85
00:08:26,780 --> 00:08:35,260
 OK, so we do a LDA hashtag, quote, P, quote, which is the ASCII value per P.

86
00:08:35,260 --> 00:08:38,820
 Now, normally we'd read this from input, but we're not going to.

87
00:08:38,820 --> 00:08:42,380
 We're just going to hard code the value we're going to convert.

88
00:08:42,380 --> 00:08:47,420
 Then we're going to compare that to the ASCII value for A.

89
00:08:47,420 --> 00:08:51,900
 So that comparison then sets the Z and the N.

90
00:08:51,900 --> 00:08:59,140
 And then we're going to say BMI to location 08, which we'll talk about this in a second,

91
00:08:59,140 --> 00:09:02,540
 how that works, how you know that that's 08.

92
00:09:02,540 --> 00:09:07,580
 That's kind of tricky, but that's an address in instruction memory, the 08.

93
00:09:07,580 --> 00:09:13,340
 And then if it's minus, we will skip the next instruction.

94
00:09:13,340 --> 00:09:17,620
 But if it's not minus, we're going to subtract 20, a hex 20,

95
00:09:17,620 --> 00:09:19,020
 because that's converting to lowercase.

96
00:09:19,020 --> 00:09:23,940
 If you look at the ASCII table, you see that the difference between an uppercase A

97
00:09:23,940 --> 00:09:27,340
 and a lowercase A is 20.

98
00:09:27,340 --> 00:09:32,260
 The lowercase A is 20 hex higher than an uppercase A.

99
00:09:32,260 --> 00:09:38,100
 And then that BMI 08, if it's already uppercase, meaning it's a lower number,

100
00:09:38,100 --> 00:09:40,460
 that jumps to the BRK and the program stops.

101
00:09:40,460 --> 00:09:47,300
 You can think of this as if the accumulator is less than the letter A,

102
00:09:47,300 --> 00:09:49,820
 we're going to skip the next instruction.

103
00:09:49,820 --> 00:09:55,140
 And if we don't skip, we're going to subtract 20 hex.

104
00:09:55,140 --> 00:09:56,740
 And if we do skip, we're done.

105
00:09:56,740 --> 00:10:00,860
 And then in the accumulator will be the uppercase letter, whether or not

106
00:10:00,860 --> 00:10:07,940
 the original letter that was loaded into the accumulator was uppercase or lowercase.

107
00:10:07,940 --> 00:10:11,100
 And so this is where flow charts come back.

108
00:10:11,100 --> 00:10:15,540
 Remember I said flow charts are not cool, although if you ask AI,

109
00:10:15,540 --> 00:10:18,660
 often flow charts are cool, they're very retro.

110
00:10:18,660 --> 00:10:24,260
 Well, the key to flow charts is that they work exactly like assembly

111
00:10:24,260 --> 00:10:26,220
 and machine language.

112
00:10:26,220 --> 00:10:28,680
 So if we look at the first instruction, which

113
00:10:28,680 --> 00:10:33,700
 is loading the accumulator with the letter, the lowercase P,

114
00:10:33,700 --> 00:10:35,420
 then we're doing a compare instruction.

115
00:10:35,420 --> 00:10:37,260
 So the compare instruction is not something

116
00:10:37,260 --> 00:10:38,860
 we think of in a high level language.

117
00:10:38,860 --> 00:10:40,620
 We're asking a question.

118
00:10:40,620 --> 00:10:45,860
 We're like, huh, compare the accumulator to A and set the flags.

119
00:10:45,860 --> 00:10:47,940
 That's what the compare instruction is doing.

120
00:10:47,940 --> 00:10:54,920
 Is accumulator equal to less than or greater than A?

121
00:10:54,920 --> 00:11:01,100
 And so then we say, was the result of that particular compare a BMI?

122
00:11:01,100 --> 00:11:05,420
 Negative, because BMI means is the N flag set?

123
00:11:05,420 --> 00:11:13,020
 And if the N flag is set, we're going to jump to instruction memory location 08.

124
00:11:13,020 --> 00:11:15,340
 If not, we're going to fall through.

125
00:11:15,340 --> 00:11:22,580
 And by the way, the actual $0.08 is in the immediately following instruction

126
00:11:22,580 --> 00:11:24,420
 memory.

127
00:11:24,420 --> 00:11:28,500
 And so where to jump is the 08.

128
00:11:28,500 --> 00:11:33,180
 Then if we don't jump, we're going to subtract 20 hex.

129
00:11:33,180 --> 00:11:36,180
 And the 20 is also in immediate memory.

130
00:11:36,180 --> 00:11:44,260
 And then the place the program stops is at instruction memory 0x08.

131
00:11:44,260 --> 00:11:47,940
 So the way, if you're doing this by hand,

132
00:11:47,940 --> 00:11:53,380
 you would actually kind of leave instruction memory 05 blank,

133
00:11:53,380 --> 00:11:59,260
 lay everything else out, and then you see where 0x08, the halt, works.

134
00:11:59,260 --> 00:12:06,540
 And then you would go copy that back in to the 0x05 memory location.

135
00:12:06,540 --> 00:12:11,860
 That seems painful, painful even for eight instructions.

136
00:12:11,860 --> 00:12:15,580
 Thankfully, we have this thing called assembly language.

137
00:12:15,580 --> 00:12:18,820
 So there's no need to compute these instructions by hand.

138
00:12:18,820 --> 00:12:24,100
 And so if you look at the BMI in this code, you say BMI skip.

139
00:12:24,100 --> 00:12:26,540
 And then right before the instruction that you want to skip to,

140
00:12:26,540 --> 00:12:29,940
 you put a little label with a colon, so skip colon.

141
00:12:29,940 --> 00:12:33,700
 Now it turns out that, just like I told you on the last slide,

142
00:12:33,700 --> 00:12:36,580
 the assembler is making two passes.

143
00:12:36,580 --> 00:12:40,940
 It literally is assembling all the code and remembering where

144
00:12:40,940 --> 00:12:42,980
 it needs to change addresses.

145
00:12:42,980 --> 00:12:46,180
 So it kind of keeps track of, that's going to wherever skip turns out

146
00:12:46,180 --> 00:12:48,460
 to be, because skip could be later.

147
00:12:48,460 --> 00:12:50,740
 So it has to do it all, has to lay it all out,

148
00:12:50,740 --> 00:12:52,980
 has to figure out where it's going to go in the memory,

149
00:12:52,980 --> 00:12:57,900
 and has to go back and replace the skip with the 8 hex,

150
00:12:57,900 --> 00:12:59,300
 so that it knows what it's doing.

151
00:12:59,300 --> 00:13:00,940
 But for us, we don't care.

152
00:13:00,940 --> 00:13:02,180
 We write assembly language.

153
00:13:02,180 --> 00:13:03,380
 We use labels.

154
00:13:03,380 --> 00:13:09,060
 And the whole notion that you've got to do two passes by hand,

155
00:13:09,060 --> 00:13:11,140
 we just write assembly language.

156
00:13:11,140 --> 00:13:18,580
 And so our larger example codes will be assembly language.

157
00:13:18,580 --> 00:13:23,340
 And so the jumps, like I said, are far simpler than if logic.

158
00:13:23,340 --> 00:13:27,860
 So in addition to the beq, the branch equal, branch not equal,

159
00:13:27,860 --> 00:13:32,980
 branch minus, and branch plus, we also have an unconditional jump.

160
00:13:32,980 --> 00:13:36,740
 That's ignoring, you jump to an address.

161
00:13:36,740 --> 00:13:41,620
 That just says, don't look at the flags, just unconditionally jump.

162
00:13:41,620 --> 00:13:44,380
 But just think about this for a second.

163
00:13:44,380 --> 00:13:49,580
 The PC, the program counter, is itself a register.

164
00:13:49,580 --> 00:13:57,780
 So even though we have these opcodes that say branch, sure, or jump,

165
00:13:57,780 --> 00:14:01,820
 in a sense, you could think of these as just a set of the PC.

166
00:14:01,820 --> 00:14:07,380
 If we had a assembly language that said set PC to this address,

167
00:14:07,380 --> 00:14:12,820
 then that would mean that the PC, the next time it would retrieve an instruction,

168
00:14:12,820 --> 00:14:14,060
 would go to where it's at.

169
00:14:14,060 --> 00:14:19,860
 So you can think of a jump as set the PC to this address.

170
00:14:19,860 --> 00:14:23,660
 Or a jump conditional says, if this condition is true,

171
00:14:23,660 --> 00:14:25,660
 set the PC to this address.

172
00:14:25,660 --> 00:14:29,620
 And of course, these are all 16-bit instructions.

173
00:14:29,620 --> 00:14:37,900
 And so that address is in the immediately following memory location, OK?

174
00:14:37,900 --> 00:14:43,860
 So there are also no for and while loops in machine language.

175
00:14:43,860 --> 00:14:47,780
 And so we have to construct them with these comparisons

176
00:14:47,780 --> 00:14:49,900
 and conditional branching.

177
00:14:49,900 --> 00:14:54,180
 So I'm not going to bother showing you the machine language for this.

178
00:14:54,180 --> 00:14:56,700
 The emulator will allow you to see that.

179
00:14:56,700 --> 00:14:58,340
 I'm just going to show you the assembly.

180
00:14:58,340 --> 00:15:01,460
 So on the left is assembly language.

181
00:15:01,460 --> 00:15:06,660
 And assembly language is a textual language that is not zeros and ones,

182
00:15:06,660 --> 00:15:12,160
 but there is a one-to-one correspondence that every single assembly language

183
00:15:12,160 --> 00:15:15,300
 statement turns directly into machine language.

184
00:15:15,300 --> 00:15:19,460
 Now it might be an 8-bit machine language or a 16-bit machine language.

185
00:15:19,460 --> 00:15:25,020
 And the assembler, which is a program that converts this text to machine language,

186
00:15:25,020 --> 00:15:30,180
 the assembler knows all the rules, the syntax of the pound sign 5.

187
00:15:30,180 --> 00:15:33,380
 So really, while we have been talking about machine language,

188
00:15:33,380 --> 00:15:36,020
 we mostly have been talking about assembly language.

189
00:15:36,020 --> 00:15:38,260
 So let's take a look at a really simple for loop.

190
00:15:38,260 --> 00:15:40,220
 Now this for loop doesn't do anything.

191
00:15:40,220 --> 00:15:42,540
 It's just constructing this for loop.

192
00:15:42,540 --> 00:15:45,100
 Or a while loop, it's a top-tested loop.

193
00:15:45,100 --> 00:15:48,060
 So if we go through this, the first thing we do--

194
00:15:48,060 --> 00:15:51,900
 and I mentioned that x registers are good for loops and arrays.

195
00:15:51,900 --> 00:15:55,620
 First thing we're going to do is we're going to clear the x register.

196
00:15:55,620 --> 00:15:57,380
 Then we're going to have a label that says,

197
00:15:57,380 --> 00:16:00,580
 here's a place we're going to come back to.

198
00:16:00,580 --> 00:16:02,260
 But that doesn't take up any memory.

199
00:16:02,260 --> 00:16:06,060
 That just is something that the assembler is going to remember that location,

200
00:16:06,060 --> 00:16:07,820
 wherever that location is.

201
00:16:07,820 --> 00:16:10,500
 Then we're going to compare the x register to 5.

202
00:16:10,500 --> 00:16:14,020
 That's saying, huh, hey, let's just look at x.

203
00:16:14,020 --> 00:16:17,500
 Let's look at 5 and then set the z and the n flags.

204
00:16:17,500 --> 00:16:20,380
 And beq to end.

205
00:16:20,380 --> 00:16:21,980
 End is a label in this case.

206
00:16:21,980 --> 00:16:28,620
 So if x equals 5, we're going to jump to the end label.

207
00:16:28,620 --> 00:16:31,220
 If we're not jumping, we're coming through,

208
00:16:31,220 --> 00:16:35,420
 we're going to add 1 to x, which is the INX instruction, or x

209
00:16:35,420 --> 00:16:37,100
 equals x plus 1.

210
00:16:37,100 --> 00:16:42,660
 Now on this right-hand side, these x's are not really just any old variable.

211
00:16:42,660 --> 00:16:44,540
 That means the x register.

212
00:16:44,540 --> 00:16:48,460
 So there's only the accumulator and the x and the y

213
00:16:48,460 --> 00:16:51,100
 and program counter and instruction register.

214
00:16:51,100 --> 00:16:52,580
 But these are not variables.

215
00:16:52,580 --> 00:16:55,900
 These are just plain old registers.

216
00:16:55,900 --> 00:17:00,460
 So after the INX instruction, we do an unconditional jump.

217
00:17:00,460 --> 00:17:03,620
 And you can see that on the flow chart on the right-hand side,

218
00:17:03,620 --> 00:17:07,020
 perfectly represented to jump back to loop.

219
00:17:07,020 --> 00:17:08,300
 Now where is loop?

220
00:17:08,300 --> 00:17:09,940
 What number is loop?

221
00:17:09,940 --> 00:17:10,820
 We don't know.

222
00:17:10,820 --> 00:17:11,940
 And we don't care.

223
00:17:11,940 --> 00:17:14,780
 But the assembler is going to turn that before it gets loaded

224
00:17:14,780 --> 00:17:16,500
 into the memories machine language.

225
00:17:16,500 --> 00:17:20,340
 Loop becomes a number, just like end becomes a number.

226
00:17:20,340 --> 00:17:22,160
 So we jump to the top of the loop.

227
00:17:22,160 --> 00:17:24,940
 And you can see that we added 1 to x.

228
00:17:24,940 --> 00:17:26,060
 And then we compare it to x.

229
00:17:26,060 --> 00:17:29,460
 We check the branch, which in the second time around,

230
00:17:29,460 --> 00:17:32,140
 it goes straight down and adds 1 again.

231
00:17:32,140 --> 00:17:33,980
 So you can see this is a for loop that's going

232
00:17:33,980 --> 00:17:39,700
 to go round and round and round until x is equal to 5.

233
00:17:39,700 --> 00:17:42,260
 And then it's going to jump to end.

234
00:17:42,260 --> 00:17:45,340
 And at end, the program is going to halt.

235
00:17:45,340 --> 00:17:48,900
 In the next section, we're going to go into--

236
00:17:48,900 --> 00:17:51,500
 we're not going to worry quite so much about the machine

237
00:17:51,500 --> 00:17:52,380
 language.

238
00:17:52,380 --> 00:17:55,020
 We're going to worry more about the assembly language.

239
00:17:55,020 --> 00:17:58,400
 So we could talk about building simple algorithms

240
00:17:58,400 --> 00:18:02,820
 in machine language, but writing them in assembly language.

241
00:18:02,820 --> 00:18:05,780
 So if you look at the summary of the machine language

242
00:18:05,780 --> 00:18:09,420
 we've talked about so far, this is not all of them.

243
00:18:09,420 --> 00:18:12,020
 But they're kind of simple.

244
00:18:12,020 --> 00:18:17,500
 You load, you compare, you jump, et cetera.

245
00:18:17,500 --> 00:18:22,220
 And you can branch and jump and clear and increment and stop.

246
00:18:22,220 --> 00:18:24,660
 And it's a real, really simple thing.

247
00:18:24,660 --> 00:18:27,980
 And it is both simple and powerful,

248
00:18:27,980 --> 00:18:33,060
 but it's actually super verbose because of its simplicity.

